                  daily produced allopregnanolone concentrations comparable to
                  physiological premenopausal levels. Confirms oral progesterone
                  serves as a prodrug to allopregnanolone. Critical pharmacological
                  evidence that oral micronized progesterone (Prometrium/Utrogestan)
                  at 100--200 mg doses will generate significant allopregnanolone.
                  Limitation: very small n; postmenopausal only; single/repeated
                  dose design without long-term data.}
}

@article{Zhao2012continuousProgesterone,
  author       = {Zhao, Liqin and Morgan, Todd E and Mao, Zisu and Lin, Song
                  and Cadenas, Enrique and Finch, Caleb E and Pike, Christian J
                  and Mack, Wendy J and Brinton, Roberta Diaz},
  title        = {Continuous versus cyclic progesterone exposure differentially
                  regulates hippocampal gene expression and functional profiles},
  journal      = {PLoS One},
  year         = {2012},
  volume       = {7},
  number       = {2},
  pages        = {e31267},
  doi          = {10.1371/journal.pone.0031267},
  pmid         = {22393359},
  url          = {https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0031267},
  keywords     = {progesterone, receptor downregulation, cyclic, continuous,
                  neuroprotection, hippocampus, progesterone-mecfs},
  research_stream = {progesterone-mecfs},
  certainty    = {0.38},
  note         = {Animal study (ovariectomized rats) comparing continuous vs cyclic
                  progesterone + estradiol regimens. Cyclic progesterone maintained
                  neuroprotective gene expression profiles; continuous progesterone
                  mimicked hormone-depleted (OVX) conditions across bioenergetics and
                  inflammatory pathways. Key safety/efficacy concern for ME/CFS
                  hypothesis: continuous oral progesterone may cause receptor
                  downregulation / loss of effect. Implies cyclic dosing (e.g.\ 14
                  days on, 14 days off) preferable to continuous exposure.
                  Limitation: rodent model; translational relevance uncertain.}
}

@article{AndreenBackstrom2009negMood,
  author       = {Andr{\'e}en, Lisa and Nyberg, Sigrid and Turkmen, S{\"u}heyla
                  and van Wingen, Guido and Fern{\'a}ndez, Guillén
                  and B{\"a}ckstr{\"o}m, Torb{\"j}{\"o}rn},
